{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17418520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17418520"},"attributes":{"position":2,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T10:36:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T10:36:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261521"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261521"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11632"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510638"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:32:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:32:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11632"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261521"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T10:36:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:37:56+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":5,"questionsAnswered":5,"marksTotal":5,"marksAttainable":5,"marksAttempted":5,"finishedAt":null,"resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.4,"questionsCorrect":2,"marksCorrect":2},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"11632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11632"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.02,0.55,0.02,0.31]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4259"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109974"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4259","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4259"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11632"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92333"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3758"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5663"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6945"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6994"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10402"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10531"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11894"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13659"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30393"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31092"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37235"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109974"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a one-day history of fever. She has no other symptoms such as abdominal pain, diarrhoea, vomiting, dysuria, dyspnoea or headache. She has a medical history of triple-negative breast cancer, for which she completed a course of paclitaxel chemotherapy eight days ago. She has no other significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 130/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 15/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.7\u00b0C. Abdominal, cardiovascular and respiratory examinations are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal neutrophil count of 0.3 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (2.0-7.0). A full septic screen including urine microscopy and culture, blood cultures, and chest X-ray have been performed (all unremarkable at time of review).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral ciprofloxacin plus amoxicillin/clavulanate","Oral fluconazole","Intravenous piperacillin-tazobactam","Intravenous vancomycin","Intravenous piperacillin-tazobactam plus vancomycin"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFebrile neutropenia is a concerning and potentially life-threatening complication of chemotherapy in patients with cancer and is associated with significant morbidity and mortality. Prompt identification, monitoring and treatment are critical in managing this oncologic emergency. Febrile neutropenia is defined as a temperature \u226538.3\u00b0C or \u226538.0\u00b0C for \u22651 hour, with an absolute neutrophil count \u0026lt;0.5 \u00d7 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L or expected to decrease to \u0026lt;0.5 \u00d7 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L within 48 hours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the case of a febrile neutropaenic patient who is hemodynamically stable, and without localising symptoms, the most important next step in management is to start monotherapy with a broad-spectrum, anti-pseudomonal beta-lactam intravenously such as\u003Cstrong\u003E piperacillin-tazobactam\u003C/strong\u003E. Broad-spectrum antibiotics are indicated due to the uncertainty of the causative organism and the high risk associated with delayed treatment given the immunosuppressed state.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous piperacillin-tazobactam plus vancomycin\u003C/strong\u003E is not the preferred management in this case as the patient is relatively stable without any hemodynamic instabilities. Vancomycin may be considered if there is concern for methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA) infection, suspicion of catheter-related infection, skin or soft tissue infections, pneumonia, or haemodynamic instability. However, it is initially not indicated empirically to avoid the unnecessary risks and adverse effects of vancomycin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVancomycin\u003C/strong\u003E monotherapy would be inappropriate as it lacks adequate gram-negative coverage and the gram-positive coverage may not be as rapidly effective as a beta-lactam.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral ciprofloxacin plus amoxicillin/clavulanate \u003C/strong\u003Ehas broad spectrum coverage and is an alternative regimen for the treatment of febrile neutropenia, particularly as ciprofloxacin is the only oral antibiotic that provides coverage against pseudomonas. Low-risk patients (i.e. anticipated brief duration period of neutropenia within 7 days of receiving treatment) can receive initial oral or IV empirical antibiotic doses in a clinic or hospital setting and may be transitioned to outpatient oral or IV treatment. However, oral antibiotics alone may not be preferred in this case as intravenous antibiotics provide a more rapid onset of action and greater absorption. Therefore IV piperacillin-tazobactam remains the most appropriate form of management, given its broad spectrum coverage and anti-pseudomonal effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral fluconazole\u003C/strong\u003E serves as an antifungal prophylaxis which is recommended in high-risk patients with persistent fever after 4-7 days of broad-spectrum antibacterial regimen and a suspicion of fungal infection, hence is not indicated in this case. However, it is important to consider fungal infections by Candida or Aspergillus species in patients with persistent neutropenia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Febrile neutropenia is defined as a temperature \u226538.3\u00b0C or \u226538.0\u00b0C for \u22651 hour, with an absolute neutrophil count \u003C0.5 \u00d7 10^9/L or expected to decrease to \u003C0.5 \u00d7 10^9/L within 48 hours.","Broad-spectrum anti-pseudomonal beta-lactams should be given to patients suspected of febrile neutropenia.","Patients presenting with febrile neutropenia should be admitted for assessment and review."],"references":["Freifeld AG, Bow EJ, Sepkowitz KA, Boeckh MJ, Ito JI, Mullen CA, Raad II, Rolston KV, Young JA, Wingard JR, Infectious Diseases Society of America. Clinical practice guideline for the use of antimicrobial agents in neutropenic patients with cancer: 2010 update by the infectious diseases society of america. Clin Infect Dis. 2011;52(4):e56. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21258094/","de Naurois J, Novitzky-Basso I, Gill MJ, Marti FM, Cullen MH, Roila F; ESMO Guidelines Working Group. Management of febrile neutropenia: ESMO Clinical Practice Guidelines. Ann Oncol. 2010 May;21 Suppl 5:v252-6. doi: 10.1093/annonc/mdq196. PMID: 20555092. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20555092/","Punnapuzha S, Edemobi PK, Elmoheen A. Febrile Neutropenia. [Updated 2023 Mar 30]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK541102/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92333"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11632"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92333","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92333"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-27T19:09:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-27T19:09:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4259"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109974"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https: